May 20 2009 	Decent basic level accommodation in an expensive city	We only stayed one night here on honeymoon before going on a week's trip to Hawaii and simply wanted somewhere not very expensive to spend a night. In this regard the hotel fitted the bill. The room was old fashioned and basic, and reasonably clean. The amenities were not as good as I'd like though. We arrived from the airport late at night and I was very thirsty and wanted a drink, but the only option (there was no hotel bar open and no minibar) was to wander the floors looking for a vending machine/ice machine. There was only 1 on each floor and the first couple I found were broken so I had to visit several floors just to get a drink. To get food we had to call a delivery company for a pizza. The location is quite &quot;interesting&quot;, not far from some of the dodgy areas of SF, so you wouldn't want to wonder around outside at night. During the day it's fine although you will likely get beggers asking for money if you're obviously a tourist. I asked the hotel if they would store a spare suitcase (we didn't need all our luggage in Hawaii) for the week we were away and they refused to do so. They said they didn't have anywhere to store it, which seems pretty hard to believe in such a huge building. So instead we asked the Hotel Kabuki (where we stayed on our return) if they would do this and they were more than happy to help. So a definite black mark against the Whitcomb and a gold star to the Kabuki. Upon check-out I would say that the hotel were good in that they helped me do an online check-in for our flight from their business room. Overall this hotel was adequate in that it gave us a fairly cheap place to spend a night. However I thought the overall experience/lack of facilities matched the price we paid and therefore I would only recommend it to those travelling on a tight budget.	
