Jan 6 2009 	Know what you pay for.	My boyfriend and I stayed here during a stop on our road trip down the coast. I paid about $70 for a non-smoking room with a queen bed, which was advertised as 50% off the original price (~$140) on Hotels.com the week after Thanksgiving 2008. I thought, &quot;Wow...it's 50% off and it's a historic hotel. I'm there.&quot; I checked the reviews on TripAdvisor and saw that it recieved mediocre reviews mostly due to its poor parking situation and room conditions. I thought I'd give it a go anyway.A few days before I was supposed to arrive at Hotel Whitcomb, I called to push my reservation back a day. That was easy. I checked to see what its current rates were after I hung up. My room was still going for about $70 at regular price! I got duped. I'm usually good about recognizing a phony &quot;sale&quot;, but this time I didn't.Here's the fun part - figuring out where to park when you DO get to the hotel! First of all, San Francisco is disorienting. There was no where for us to stop the car and see where either the public parking or valet was. There were no plainly posted signs! After circling around for awhile trying to find parking, my boyfriend, who was driving, tried the alley between Hotel Whitcomb and the building next door. It took us right to valet parking! Whitcomb needs to put a sign somewhere, seriously. After that fun experience, we figured we'd pay the $28/day for valet. At the registrars desk is a sign that says valet is $28/day plus tax...its website never mentioned tax! I was determined to keep an open mind about the rest of the hotel. The lobby level looks nice. There is antique looking furniture (or at least non-pressboard with veneer furniture) and many chandeliers. The elevators have a special ding when the doors open. The room (at least ours) looked fitting for a historic hotel room. Though, upon closer inspection I noticed the furniture was pressboard with veneer. Don't let this deter you. I was expecting there to be furniture from the time period it was built. (I stayed at a historic house in York, England that had antique furniture.) Expecting antique furniture for a $70 room (in a hotel with 460 rooms) wasn't realistic.My real beef with the room was there was one washcloth (for two registered guests...we had to call the front desk twice the first of two nights to get them to bring more and they still only left one the second night), the space around the sink faucet wasn't clean and had a hair stuck to it (I cleaned it myself), the bathroom door wouldn't shut because the latch was stuck in the door, there were stains on our blanket duvet, and no free breakfast (not even continental) was offered. Also, down the hall from us were a group of college-aged looking people who were noisy (and we are 23 ourselves!)One good thing that sort of counterbalanced some of the bad, was the concierge. Michelle, who is the gift shop cashier and the hotel concierge, is fantastic! She grew up in San Francisco and knows it quite well. She knows what's worth seeing and what's plain touristy. She can make a public transportation route based on your activities for the day. Even though SF's public transportation is really good, it was really confusing. Michelle's help was valuable because my boyfriend and I only had one day in SF and we hadn't done much research.So here's the breakdown...1. If you plan on driving here, know the parking situation.2. Don't expect much for $70.3. Don't expect elegancy. Though it portrays itself as elegant, it is not - evidenced by the staff's and the hotel resident's mannerisms, and also by the homeless outside.4. The cleanliness is iffy inside the rooms.Remember...do research before chosing any hotel, motel, inn, B&amp;B, etc.!	
