Jan 15 2008 	Hotel Whitcomb Worked for Us	We stayed here to be close to our early morning weekend wedding at SF City Hall. Got great rates thru the Trip Rewards website using the AAA rate option. We booked several rooms – one for us (bride and groom), one for bridal party, out of town parents, photographer, etc…This hotel was picked due to the proximity to city hall and because of the historic background. (It once served as city hall briefly). We had even considered having the wedding in their ballroom – but opted for city hall instead.We had a variety of room types – from a queen (1 bed) room – 2 double beds – king suite….Everyone was satisfied with their accommodations. The beds were comfy and the wifi worked well for everyone that tried it.T.J, one of the hotel’s managers, treated us wonderfully at check-in (Thursday, January 3) and was very patient – even though I had several reservations and was checking in people that had not even arrived yet. He even upgraded our room to a suite when he found out about our upcoming wedding. The room had a fantastic view of city hall. He offered a crib when he found out one of the guests would be bringing a baby. (We had brought a play yard - but the offer and attention to detail was not overlooked) Champagne (and a very nice candy and fruit basket) was sent up to our room to help us celebrate. We do not drink, but we ate that chocolate!Pros: good rates, good customer service, clean, decent parking rates (valet parking is $28 a night here - compared to over $40 we paid at the Palace Hotel --- and other SF hotels are even more – it is San Francisco …you pay to park EVERYWHERE, just plan on it)Cons: This hotel is a victim of their neighborhood somewhat – but they do have a good security staff that handles their front door and we always felt safe. Also, parking at this hotel can be a tad confusing as you must pull around to the back of the hotel as that is where their parking is. If you call ahead they warn you about this and explain the process. Basically, if pass the hotel, (and it is on your right as you are traveling down Market) you turn right at the light and then turn right into the next driveway – (this can be confusing as it says “public parking”) If you pull in and tell the valet that you are a hotel guest, they take care of you, help you with bags, call a bellman etc.My only complaint is this: I made a special point to stop by the front desk (Friday afternoon, January 4) to check in our wedding photographer (she arrived a day later than the rest of the guests that stayed at the hotel) and to make sure her room was all set and she could pick up her own key when she arrived, because we would be away from the hotel, doing those last minute wedding errands. A hotel manager (Darin) handled this. Several hours later when our photographer arrived, it is lucky we were back, because, she would have had to wait for us. Seems the check-in process had not been completed, even though I had given my credit card and was assured it was all set. Luckily, the gentleman helping us was very cordial and understanding, because I was tired and annoyed.My advice about the hotel restaurant - skip it! We ate a small rehearsal breakfast here on Friday morning. (party of 7 adults, 1 baby; bill $125) The food is not bad and the prices were fair for the style of place. My complaint has to do with the service. Despite there being only two other very small tables in the place, we waited – for everything. One guest finally gave up on getting mayo for his sandwich and ate it dry. Coffee was never refilled - my son-in-law finally got up, got the coffee pot himself and placed it on the table. Dad’s milk was spoiled (he got another glass- but it took a while) and some drinks were finally served mid meal after repeated requests. I would hate to think what the service would be like if they were actually busy. If you want decent prices, good food and good service – walk across the street to Sam’s Diner..My advice about parking and getting around (especially at night): We left our cars parked for the most part and took cabs everywhere – it is just easier and usually more cost effective than driving in this area of the city.All in all, this is a very good 3 star property, by any standards, actually higher if you compare it to most other 3 star properties in San Francisco. If you go there expecting that you should fine. If you go expecting a 5 star place – you may not be happy.We were happy enough there to extend our stay beyond what we originally planned. Thank you, T.J. Weddings are stressful, you made ours a little easier on us.	
Jan 9 2008 	This is San Francisco.	I suppose when reading reviews of this place, you need to know where the reviewer is coming from. We're a couple in our early 30s who was looking for a) a good price b) clean rooms c) good location. We definitely got all of the above.I had read a lot of reviews of this place after we had booked. And really though there are many homeless in the neighbourhood, I'm not sure what you'd expect being in such a central location. The location is pretty great seeing that a BART/Muni entrance is right in front. It is within easy walking distance of Union Square and other downtown attractions like the Asian American Art Museum, Yerba Buena Park, SFMOMA, Civic Center etc. It's also very close to the shops in the more recently gentrified Hayes Valley. If you're willing to do a bit more walking, Haight/Ashbury and the Castro are totally accessible. And if you're willing to be adventurous, the Tenderloin is very close. The lobby is quite beautiful, though it is an older place so the furniture is a bit worn. We spent some time in the lobby area, because the WiFi was not accessible in our room. However, I've had this problem in many establishments ranging from Travelodge to Hyatt. The halls have enough lighting and though they do sort of remind me of The Shining(as mentioned by a previous reviewer) I don't think it's a bad thing. The elevators were fine, however we did notice the elevator inspection certificates were expired. We asked for a room with two double beds instead of a single queen and we found we had ample space. The bathroom was clean and we didn't find them too small, though there was really not much of a sink counter. As in most place, the fan could be cleaner as well as the air conditioner in the room. However we didn't use the air conditioner, bec. it was winter. The sheets on one of the beds had a strange stain, but the other bed was fine. We did not have any bed bugs. Of course the sheets weren't as soft as my 600 TC Egyptian cotton from home, but they were no worse than any other hotel sheets. The towels were also standard issue hotel towels.We had a huge closet and the iron and ironing board looked new. The halls do have a bit of a strange smell, though we did not find that to be the case in our room. Overall we got a great price for our room. We stayed there 5 nights and were comfortable. I think you may be able to find a nicer hotel in San Francisco, but not for the same price. And I'm sure that you can do much worse in this price range.	
Dec 23 2007 	Decent Hotel in a mediocre neighborhood	When staying at the Hotel Whitcomb, it is important to understand what you are getting. The hotel has a nice, elegant lobby and a friendly, helpful staff. Apparently, the hotel has been around for almost a century and has a very dated feeling about it. Hallways throughout the hotel are poorly lit, and I kept thinking to myself that it was reminiscent of 'The Shining', particularly when there aren't any other guests in the halls. As for the actual rooms in the hotel, I was somewhat dissapointed. The room I stayed in was a single, queen bed room that had little room to maneuver. The room had a strong smell of disinfectant, that took a while to get used to. On the brightside, the bathroom was in great condition and looked to have been recently remodeled, although it was small and would be suited for a single occupant at a time. It is also worth noting to people who aren't familiar with San Francisco, that this hotel is located in the civic center/ downtown. While this means that the hotel is centrally located, it also means that there are alot of homeless and shady charachters around. Overall, I would reccomend the hotel to someone who enjoys older, atmospheric hotels at a good price (I paid $80 for a one-night Saturday stay). If you prefer a more contemporary hotel with more of a modern atmosphere in the downtown area, I would probably reccomend the Holiday Inn at 1500 Van Ness which is located about 10 blocks north ($125 a night for a single king-bed).	
