Mar 4 2006	Still a good budget option	I stayed here in March of 2004 (my review on tripadvisor is dated March 24, 2004), and on my trip last year stayed at the Westin St. Francis. I got my hotels at Priceline all times, the Westin for $73/night and the Ramada (both times) for $45/night. If you're traveling on a strict budget, the Ramada is not a bad choice. Wireless net access is now included, like a previous reviewer I found it dodgy (the signal would get lost) but I did not have a problem with spyware. I used the fitness center in the hotel room on this stay - it is a small room on the mezzanine with two treadmills, a recumbent cycle and a regular one and a stair climber as well as a not very good Universal machine. It isn't great but fine for a weekend stay. Hotel staff, especially the front desk, is very friendly and helpful. Oddly enough I was given the same room as last stay (perhaps because I only need a single bed instead of two). I like the decor, which is period to the hotel's construction (I'm sure it's been refurbished and is in decent condition); the bathroom though is very basic and the towels are thin and skimpy.There is still a problem with vagrancy around the Civic Center area, but I didn't feel unsafe. To look on the bright side, the hotel is incredibly convenient to Civic Center including the Opera House and Symphony, the Performing Arts Museum and the Asian Art Museum. Walk one block from the hotel up to Larkin and then cross Market and pass the Civic Center a few blocks to Eddy Street and you are at Saigon Sandwich, which has sinfully good Banh Mi. That area (the Tenderloin, now being called &quot;Little Saigon&quot;) is filled with good Asian food.Looking at pictures of the St. Francis and recalling that trip, I felt much more pampered for about $40 per day more, including the fees for dial up access and the health club. If I had the money to spare, I'd spring for it. But I got everything I need at a cost of $54/day at the Ramada including all taxes and fees. I'll stay here again.	
